<doc docid="1a048b5fb0ab38813c5815d8c82fc89b" genre="news" origlang="xx">
<seg id="1">Institutions shift to growth assets</seg>
<seg id="2">Europe has become the focus as big investors look to take advantage of its recovery Source: AP</seg>
<seg id="3">IS capital growth back in vogue?</seg>
<seg id="4">That certainly would seem to be the case, based on the preferred asset allocation strategies of institutional fund managers in the US, Europe and Australia.</seg>
<seg id="5">Six to eight months ago, most fund managers still were firmly focused on yield.</seg>
<seg id="6">The aim of the game was to lock in holdings that delivered good income returns, with high-yielding stocks with stable or rising earnings top of the list.</seg>
<seg id="7">But that game has changed somewhat in recent months, with the smell of global economic recovery (despite the fragility of the present US debt repayment plan) spurring a shift towards undervalued stocks with strong capital growth potential.</seg>
<seg id="8">As well as equities, investors are shifting into alternative investments such as infrastructure, hedge funds and private equity.</seg>
<seg id="9">What's more, institutional investors are reducing exposure to US equities and bonds while increasing exposure to Europe, emerging markets and direct real estate.</seg>
<seg id="10">It's a fickle game, though.</seg>
<seg id="11">Institutions have no qualms about shifting their money around as opportunities arise, and that is spurring volume movements in some stocks as funds come in and out of the share register.</seg>
<seg id="12">We've heard for some time now that the US recovery is under way and that investors should be looking to park some capital into US equities.</seg>
<seg id="13">If you were holding back, fearful that the US recovery was a false dawn, you may well have missed your chance to get in early.</seg>
<seg id="14">Indeed, right now institutional investors are reducing exposure to US equities and bonds while increasing exposure to Europe, emerging markets and direct real estate.</seg>
<seg id="15">A report recently released by AMP Capital shows that institutional investors have been fine-tuning their investing approach by complementing yield holdings with growth assets, with 77 per cent confirming they now favour capital growth over yield assets.</seg>
<seg id="16">Institutional investors are reacting to the prospect of the US Federal Reserve tapering its stimulus program and higher interest rates in the US and Europe by continuing to shift assets out of public markets and into alternatives, according to the AMP Capital Institutional Investor Research Report.</seg>
<seg id="17">In the equity space, Europe has become the focus as big investors look to take advantage of a recovery in that region.</seg>
<seg id="18">While there has been a shift towards growth, however, yield still has a part to play although in new forms.</seg>
<seg id="19">"The survey has found investors are favouring investments that offer value, potential for capital growth and predictable, consistent yields as global economies continue to improve," AMP Capital chief executive international and head of global clients Anthony Fasso says.</seg>
<seg id="20">As such, they are allocating more to alternatives and, in particular, real assets.</seg>
<seg id="21">One appeal of real assets is their tangibility, which offers greater stability and insulation from the risk of public equity markets.</seg>
<seg id="22">Allocations to high-yield corporate bonds are expected to lift, while demand for real assets such as direct property, infrastructure and infrastructure debt is also on the rise, with the stable bond-like payment structure providing predictable and consistent returns across the mid to long term.</seg>
<seg id="23">In fact, the greatest demand from institutions is for direct real estate and US property market has seen heavy action in recent times as prices recover.</seg>
<seg id="24">This interest in real assets is certainly something Australian retail investors can identify with.</seg>
<seg id="25">Indeed, it seems some Australian retail investors may be ahead of our financial institutions, with the early moves of private investors into property in recent months signalled by the lift in investor loans at the major banks.</seg>
<seg id="26">As Credit Suisse's recent 2013 wealth report highlighted, Australians have much more of their wealth in non-financial assets - that is, property - than the global average.</seg>
<seg id="27">Australian investors looking to join the quest for growth will probably be considering investing in overseas markets.</seg>
<seg id="28">But timing is everything.</seg>
<seg id="29">David McDonald, head of research at Credit Suisse Australia, advises caution in the short term because of events in the US and Europe.</seg>
<seg id="30">"The last 12 months were very good for returns, particularly for equities globally as well as in Australia, and we would expect things to be a bit more modest going forward," he says.</seg>
<seg id="31">There are a few issues out there in the short term in the US, and even in Europe and elsewhere, and when markets have had a big rise like that they can react sometimes to those wobbles a bit more.</seg>
<seg id="32">But McDonald suggests such caution in relation to offshore markets should just be short term.</seg>
<seg id="33">Over the very long term we're still positive on equities and other growth assets like real estate.</seg>
<seg id="34">Looking into next year, we still see the world recovering quite well.</seg>
<seg id="35">It seems that Europe's starting to pick up, China seems to be stable, so we think the opportunities down the track are quite positive.</seg>
<seg id="36">McDonald points to emerging markets as an investment opportunity, from a capital appreciation perspective and as a currency play.</seg>
<seg id="37">If you look at the projections, focusing on growth, Asia ex-Japan is likely to grow strongly and Asia including Japan will overtake America as the wealthiest region by 2018.</seg>
<seg id="38">Obviously that has some investment implications in terms of investment opportunities and exposure to that growth.</seg>
<seg id="39">Tony Kaye is the editor of Eureka Report.</seg>
<seg id="40">To read more by him and other experts, go to www.eurekareport.com.au.</seg>
</doc>
