<seg id="1">Mongol bikies 'ready to kill police'</seg>
<seg id="2">Mongol bikies are arming themselves and are ready to kill police, Queensland officers are being warned.</seg>
<seg id="3">Source: Supplied</seg>
<seg id="4">POLICE in Queensland are being warned about their security following threats that Mongol bikies are ready to kill to avoid arrest under new anti-gang laws.</seg>
<seg id="5">Officers have been told of the threat in a confidential memo that's been published in the media.</seg>
<seg id="6">It says information dated Monday, October 28 "indicates the Mongols criminal motorcycle gang have discussed the possibility of killing any police officer who attempt (sic) to arrest them for a serious offence."</seg>
<seg id="7">Information suggests the Mongols are currently seeking multiple automatic firearms whilst a member of the Black Uhlans CMG was previously confirmed to have sought to obtain automatic firearms (M16 and AK47) on behalf of the Mongols and Finks CMG.</seg>
<seg id="8">This anticipation of escalating violence is said to be a result of legislation mandating automatic custodial sentences of up to 15 years imprisonment.</seg>
<seg id="9">The Mongols are said to believe killing a police officer to evade arrest is worth the risk to escape the lengthy custodial sentence.</seg>
<seg id="10">The memo adds that so far the threats are non-specific in nature, and are not targeted at specific members of the police service.</seg>
<seg id="11">Police have issued a formal statement repeating the threats are not specific, and saying police had been warned about personal security issues.</seg>
<seg id="12">For operational reasons it would be inappropriate to comment further.</seg>
<seg id="13">Under the new laws, bikies convicted of serious crimes face hefty additional jail terms simply for being members of declared criminal gangs.</seg>
<seg id="14">The government has also announced plans for a bikies only jail, and says jailed members will be forced to wear pink prison garb as they spend up to 23 hours a day in solitary confinement.</seg>
<seg id="15">Police Minister Jack Dempsey says the safety of officers is the government's top priority.</seg>
<seg id="16">"All threats will be fully investigated by police and the proper precautions taken," he said in a statement.</seg>
<seg id="17">The government has assured the police commissioner that we will provide the QPS with whatever resources the commissioner requires to remove these criminal gangs and thugs from Queensland.</seg>
<seg id="18">Commissioner Ian Stewart has said a review is underway to determine if police should be given more powerful guns and body armour in response to the bikie gang threat.</seg>
