<seg id="1">A good year just got better for Yalumba's Ashley Ratcliff</seg>
<seg id="2">Ashley Ratcliff has received awards for his exploration of alternative heat-loving grape varieties.</seg>
<seg id="3">Picture: Michael Marshall Source: News Limited</seg>
<seg id="4">IT'S been a very good year for Ashley Ratcliff.</seg>
<seg id="5">The Barossa-based viticulturist manages Yalumba's extensive vineyard in South Australia's Riverland region, and in the past couple of months he's won three major awards for his groundbreaking way with grapevines.</seg>
<seg id="6">The gongs started coming in September when Ashley was named Horticultural Grower of the Year by ABC Rural.</seg>
<seg id="7">A few days later he picked up the Wine Industry Award at the Riverland Wine Show - an award normally given to winemakers.</seg>
<seg id="8">And last week he was named Viticulturist of the Year by the prestigious Australian Society of Viticulture and Oenology.</seg>
<seg id="9">It's about bloody time hard-working viticulturists such as Ashley received this kind of public recognition.</seg>
<seg id="10">The winemakers usually take all the credit in this industry - but without talented people growing quality grapes, there's no wine at all.</seg>
<seg id="11">Ashley's awards are for his exploration of alternative, heat-loving grape varieties and his involvement, as founding chairman, with the Riverland Alternative Wine group, set up a few years ago to share information about these exciting new-to-the-region grapes.</seg>
<seg id="12">As well as working for Yalumba, he and wife Holly also have their own 40ha Riverland vineyard called Ricca Terra at Barmera, where they have planted southern Italian grapes such as vermentino, nero d'avola and grillo on drought-tolerant rootstocks and are growing them with much less irrigation and at lower yields than are common in this hot, thirsty country.</seg>
<seg id="13">Literally putting their money where his mouth is.</seg>
<seg id="14">Ashley sells all the grapes from his own vineyard, mostly to large wineries in the region such as his bosses at Yalumba, to Angoves and Salena Estate.</seg>
<seg id="15">But this last vintage, 2013, he also sold some of the red nero d'avola grapes to two very small wineries a long way away: Bellwether Wines all the way down in Coonawarra and Wine by Brad all the way over in Margaret River.</seg>
<seg id="16">It's a fascinating exercise to taste them side-by-side: two completely different end results from the same raw materials.</seg>
<seg id="17">The 2013 Bellwether Nero d'Avola Rose (about $25) is the palest of pale salmon in colour but packs a mighty punch of flavour, with the juicy crisp crunch of a slightly unripe strawberry and the savoury, creamy texture of a full-bodied dry white wine.</seg>
<seg id="18">The 2013 Vino Amato Nero d'Avola ($30) from Wine by Brad, by contrast, is a bright purple-coloured, medium-bodied snappy young red lovely dark fruit and an easy manner - exactly the kind of red you want to drink, slightly chilled, on a hot summer's evening, with pizza.</seg>
<seg id="19">I've spent a lot of time talking to Ashley over the years about his visions for the Riverland - visions that have been realised with wines such as these two.</seg>
<seg id="20">And I've watched as his impressive leadership skills and extraordinary energy have helped instil a sense of optimism and pride in the region's growers and producers, despite the wine industry as a whole going through one of its toughest periods.</seg>
<seg id="21">I'm not surprised in the slightest he's won all these awards.</seg>
</doc>
