<seg id="11">"No, I (didn't say that)," he said.</seg>
<seg id="12">Mr Obeid complained about the treatment leaseholders were receiving and was of the view they should be reissued the leases.</seg>
<seg id="13">The inquiry heard suggestions Mr Obeid knew about changes to the policy as they unfolded, up until the point the decision was made to keep the leases as direct negotiations with present leaseholders.</seg>
<seg id="14">Reporters crowd Joe Tripodi as he makes his way into the ICAC inquiry.</seg>
<seg id="15">"Unequivocally I was not discussing the development of this policy with Mr Obeid," Mr Tripodi said.</seg>
<seg id="16">I have to listen to the industry....and I changed the policy.</seg>
<seg id="17">I didn't like it but given the weight of industry pressure and urging I accepted this change was the appropriate policy for the government.</seg>
<seg id="18">He agreed he met with mediator Paul Scanlan about the commercial lease agreement but denied he'd readily expressed an opinion the public tender wouldn't go ahead.</seg>
<seg id="19">"I think he has imagined the amount of inspiration he received from that meeting," he said.</seg>
<seg id="20">The inquiry continues.</seg>
<seg id="21">Joe Tripdoi's former deputy chief of staff Lynne Ashpole gave evidence to the ICAC that has put her ex-boss in an awkward position.</seg>
<seg id="22">Picture: Cameron Richardson Source: News Limited</seg>
<seg id="23">Joe Tripodi (pictured as Minister for Ports and Waterways in 2008) is now in the ICAC's sights.</seg>
