<seg id="260">Went to the Lyric Theatre to see some plays by Samuel Beckett.</seg>
<seg id="261">It was a cheap showing, one up from a dress rehearsal, but tutor Vicki was thrilled to have got us all tickets to see Billie Whitelaw (Beckett's preferred actress) in the roles.</seg>
<seg id="262">I have to admit I wasn't enjoying the show much (people talking nonsense in dustbins and making funny noises) and then, in the second half, I heard muttering from the (mostly empty) seats behind.</seg>
<seg id="263">I glanced round and saw, all alone, Samuel Beckett (the person).</seg>
<seg id="264">It was like seeing a unicorn or a Borrower.</seg>
<seg id="265">It took my breath away.</seg>
<seg id="266">I didn't look again and I didn't elbow Stella who was next to me because she'd fallen asleep and I knew she'd jolt awake noisily and show us all up.</seg>
<seg id="267">I wondered what made one person's nonsense "genius" and another's "crap..." and I wondered if it's genius if you're tall, enigmatic, reclusive, handsome... and it's crap if you're normal or short, chatty and ugly.</seg>
<seg id="268">I was just mulling it over when something AB said sprang to mind.</seg>
<seg id="269">AB is an admirer of Les Dawson.</seg>
