<seg id="1">Don't mess with the Derby</seg>
<seg id="2">Nicholas Hall riding Fawkner crosses the line during Victoria Derby Day 2012.</seg>
<seg id="3">Here are some eternal truths about the Melbourne Spring carnival: the weather will be changeable; the Caulfield Cup and the Cox Plate will be labelled "the worst ever"; the Melbourne Cup will be dubbed "the strongest ever."</seg>
<seg id="4">Someone - a trainer, usually, but occasionally an owner and this year a bookie - will call for quotas on the number of foreign runners to be introduced so that the locals get a chance to run for Australian racing's biggest prize.</seg>
<seg id="5">Just as certain is that injury, illness or misfortune will afflict some of the stars and, come the greatest of days, they won't be there.</seg>
<seg id="6">This year the unfortunate Atlantic Jewel missed out on her grand final, the Cox Plate, while long-time Cup favourite Puissance De Lune will be an absentee from the Cup after sustaining an injury in the Moonee Valley feature last weekend.</seg>
<seg id="7">There is also another hardy annual that appears at this time of year: the call for the Victoria Derby to be reduced in distance from 2500 to 2000 metres.</seg>
<seg id="8">Australia breeds sprinter-milers is the argument that is usually made.</seg>
<seg id="9">We don't have the horses to run this "extreme" distance.</seg>
<seg id="10">They are only plodders.</seg>
<seg id="11">No one is interested.</seg>
<seg id="12">It rewards mediocrity.</seg>
<seg id="13">We should put our money into races that suit the the majority of our horses.</seg>
<seg id="14">These are other reasons advanced in favour of a change.</seg>
<seg id="15">But, interestingly, it's a cry that has been somewhat muted this time round.</seg>
<seg id="16">Is it because those wishing to tinker with the classic have given up and ceded victory to traditionalists?</seg>
<seg id="17">Is it because they have had a change of heart and accepted that a test of endurance for three-year-olds, even at this early stage of their career, is not such a terrible thing?</seg>
<seg id="18">Let's hope so and that public opinion has taken a turn as punters, the racing public and professionals accept that the industry does have a need to foster young staying talent and encourage the breeding of horses designed to cover distance.</seg>
<seg id="19">Needless to say, I am an unabashed fan of the Derby at 2500 metres.</seg>
<seg id="20">It's the classic trip for a race of this nature, the supreme test of stamina for a horse in the early part of their three-year-old season.</seg>
<seg id="21">It demands strength, stamina, tenacity and a turn of foot at the business end of the race - all the qualities a top-line racehorse is expected to possess.</seg>
<seg id="22">If the race were run over 2000 metres it just wouldn't be a Derby.</seg>
<seg id="23">The French messed with their Derby, the Prix Du Jockey Club, reducing it to 2100 metres in 2005.</seg>
<seg id="24">It's still a top-line race, but it doesn't have the same je ne s'ais quoi.</seg>
<seg id="25">Between 1920 and 2005, nine three-year-olds who had won the Jockey Club went on to win Europe's greatest race, the Prix De L'Arc de Triomphe (first run in 1920).</seg>
<seg id="26">Since the race was shortened, none have.</seg>
<seg id="27">The fact that the Melbourne Cup and almost all major races run at 2200-plus in this country seem to be won by imported horses is having a psychological impact.</seg>
<seg id="28">Perhaps the realisation is growing that, unless Australia nurtures its own staying talent, the Cup will more often be won by a foreign raider or by an owner who can stump up a seven-figure sum to buy a promising stayer and bring it here to be trained by a local handler.</seg>
<seg id="29">Maybe the mood is changing, because last year's Derby, run at a decent pace and turned into a real stamina test by Damien Oliver aboard Fiveandahalfstar, turned out to be such a strong form reference, the Anthony Cummings galloper beating Mark Kavanagh's Super Cool, with Rawnaq, from the David Hayes stable, third.</seg>
<seg id="30">Super Cool came out in the autumn to win the group 1 Australian Cup, beating Fiveandahalfstar and the older gallopers.</seg>
<seg id="31">Cummings' horse then went back to Sydney and beat the older horses in the 2400-metre BMW at group 1 level.</seg>
<seg id="32">Rawnaq ran unplaced in the Zipping Classic two weeks later, and has not been seen since.</seg>
<seg id="33">But Hvasstan, fourth home, won at group 2 level in the autumn (although was subsequently disqualified) and goes round in the group 1 Mackinnon Stakes on Saturday.</seg>
<seg id="34">Escado, who ran sixth, came out and won the group 1 SA Derby in the autumn.</seg>
<seg id="35">And, of course, the leading three-year-old and last week's Cox Plate favourite It's A Dundeel ran down the track in the Derby but proved his essay over 2500 metres did him no harm by winning three group 1s in the autumn (including the ATC Derby) and then became the only horse to beat Atlantic Jewel, in the Underwood Stakes at Caulfield earlier this spring.</seg>
<seg id="36">A quick glance down the list of Derby winners over the past decade reveals that a lot of classy horses who went on to have a major impact triumphed at Flemington and took no harm from their efforts - like Sangster (who has won at group 1 level since in NZ), Lion Tamer (an Underwood Stakes winner) and Monaco Consul (a Caulfield Cup placegetter).</seg>
<seg id="37">Rebel Raider won at 100-1 in 2008, and proved that was no fluke by backing up six months later in the group 1 SA Derby.</seg>
<seg id="38">Efficient, one of the best stayers seen in the past decade, took out the Derby in 2006 while Elvstroem succeeded in 2003: he subsequently won a Caulfield Cup and triumphed on the world stage in Dubai.</seg>
<seg id="39">So here in Australia let's stick to our tradition and keep the Derby as it is.</seg>
<seg id="40">Let's ignore the French, and shout vive la difference!</seg>
</doc>
