<doc docid="c03c161cc274f4d1383c9310dfa9d5ae" genre="news" origlang="xx">
<seg id="1">Former St Kilda coach Ross Lyon's 'bizarre' final hurrah</seg>
<seg id="2">Former St Kilda coach Ross Lyon leads the Saints off the ground after the 2011 elimination final.</seg>
<seg id="3">Picture: Michael Dodge Source: Herald Sun</seg>
<seg id="4">A NEW book to mark the St Kilda Football Club's 140th anniversary reveals the depth of bitterness at coach Ross Lyon's controversial departure at the end of 2011.</seg>
<seg id="5">In Strength Through Loyalty, to be launched at a club function on Saturday, St Kilda chief executive Michael Nettlefold talks of Lyon's "bizarre" and "unusual" behaviour late in that season, and says the coach ultimately headed to Fremantle for "purely commercial" reasons.</seg>
<seg id="6">Nettlefold said he sensed there was a problem because Lyon's "behaviour had been quite unusual" over the final months of the 2011 season, culminating in a "bizarre night" when the Saints lost an elimination final to Sydney.</seg>
<seg id="7">Within 30 minutes of the final siren at Etihad Stadium, Lyon had announced the unexpected retirements of Steven Baker and Robert Eddy as well as ruckman Michael Gardiner.</seg>
<seg id="8">Nettlefold said in the ensuing days the Saints believed they had resolved several months of contract talks with Lyon's management group, Elite Sport Properties, and had scheduled a media conference for that Thursday.</seg>
<seg id="9">The date was then pushed back, and during a board meeting on the Thursday evening Nettlefold had to excuse himself from the room to take a call from Lyon, who informed him he was quitting.</seg>
<seg id="10">Nettlefold said he then phoned ESP's Craig Kelly, who confirmed Lyon and his lawyer had independently negotiated a move to Fremantle.</seg>
<seg id="11">"I was stunned by the fact it was done outside the management group ... the fact it was done externally - that was the shock to me," Nettlefold said.</seg>
<seg id="12">We had an agreement with his management group.</seg>
<seg id="13">ESP dropped Lyon as a client and the coach has since said he handled negotiations in a way that would avoid "a clear conflict of interest" because Kelly was managing then Dockers coach Mark Harvey.</seg>
<seg id="14">Lyon has asserted St Kilda was lukewarm in its approach to contract negotiations late in the season.</seg>
<seg id="15">Nettlefold disagreed: "At the time it was convenient for that to be used as a reason, but as the situation unfolded and, by Ross's own acknowledgment, it was financially driven," he said.</seg>
<seg id="16">Nettlefold suggested Lyon was torn on how to "trade out" his strong allegiance to the players and the club for a decision made "purely on a commercial basis."</seg>
<seg id="17">Among the book's other revelations about St Kilda's coaches:</seg>
<seg id="18">LYON'S candidature was put forward by former player and coach Ken Sheldon, not former Fitzroy coach Robert Walls, as has long been suspected.</seg>
<seg id="19">LYON developed his team-defence game plan in closed training sessions during the 2009 pre-season, dividing Moorabbin Oval into marked zones the players were designated to mind.</seg>
<seg id="20">FORMER assistant coach Matt Rendell says board member Grant Thomas was the driving force behind Malcolm Blight's appointment in 2001, inviting him to join the selection sub-committee so he could "woo him" for the senior role.</seg>
<seg id="21">RENDELL said suggestions Thomas wanted subsequently to replace Blight were "crap," and that he was the one man who voted to retain Blight until at least the end of 2011.</seg>
<seg id="22">The book also reveals Thomas was sacked at the end of the 2006 season after a board meeting that went until 3am.</seg>
<seg id="23">The suggestion was Thomas was seeking to take control of the club, not just the football department.</seg>
<seg id="24">There was also a widening rift between the club's board and the football department.</seg>
<seg id="25">Or, as then president Rod Butterss put it, the club had split into "them and us" camps.</seg>
<seg id="26">Butterss said that even during the season two directors "wanted to sack (Thomas), even if he won the premiership."</seg>
<seg id="27">One symptom of the rift came when Thomas organised an overseas training camp without telling the board or including it in the budget.</seg>
<seg id="28">"I read it in the newspaper," Butterss said.</seg>
<seg id="29">The tickets had been bought.</seg>
<seg id="30">Butterss also said he believed Thomas's strong bond with the young playing group "bordered on unhealthy."</seg>
<seg id="31">Strength Through Loyalty: Saints at Moorabbin and Beyond by Russell Holmesby, retails for $49.95 and is available from Saturday at saints.com.au</seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="c0769a17f679b2669c60ff4aa9f11fbf" genre="news" origlang="xx">
